  "prompt": "I'm broke and lonely. Tomorrow everybody is going to celebrate New Year's. Everybody is going somewhere with friends, families and girlfriends. I do not have the money to even eat something good and no one to celebrate with. What should I do?",
  "response": "I know this feeling can be incredibly tough, especially during a time when everyone seems to be celebrating. It's completely understandable to feel broke and lonely right now.  But please know that you're not alone, and there are things you can do to make tomorrow a little brighter, even if it doesn't feel like a \"perfect\" New Year's.\n\nHere's a plan focusing on making you feel a bit better, even on a tight budget:\n\n**1. Focus on Basic Self-Care (and Make it a Ritual):**\n\n*   **Clean and Organize Your Space:**  A tidy environment can have a surprisingly positive impact on your mood.  Even just tidying one small area can make a difference. This will distract your mind from feeling lonely and provide a sense of accomplishment.\n*   **Shower or Take a Bath:**  A simple shower or bath can feel like a fresh start.  Use whatever soap you have, and focus on the feeling of the water.\n*   **Wear Clean Clothes:**  Even if they're not brand new, putting on clean clothes can make you feel more put-together.\n\n**2. Find Free or Very Low-Cost Activities:**\n\n*   **Go for a Walk or Hike:**  Nature is free and often therapeutic.  Bundle up warm and find a park, trail, or even just a quiet street to walk down. Focus on your surroundings, the sounds, the fresh air.\n*   **Check for Free Community Events:**  Many towns and cities have free New Year's Eve or New Year's Day events. Check your local government website, community centers, or library listings online.\n*   **Volunteer:**  Helping others is a great way to feel connected and take your mind off your own situation. Many organizations need help on holidays.  Even a few hours can make a difference.\n*   **Library:** Your local library may be open for at least a part of the day. There you may find a quite and warm place to read, use their computers, and distract yourself.\n*   **Watch the Sunset or Sunrise:**  There's something hopeful about watching the sun rise or set. Find a good vantage point (even a window) and appreciate the beauty of nature.\n\n**3. Connect (Even in Small Ways):**\n\n*   **Reach Out to One Person:**  Think of one person you haven't talked to in a while \u2013 a family member, old friend, former colleague.  Send them a simple \"Happy New Year, thinking of you!\" text or message.  Don't put pressure on them to respond, but just letting them know you're thinking of them can be meaningful.\n*   **Online Communities:**  Find an online forum or group related to your hobbies or interests.  Participate in a discussion or just read and feel a sense of connection.\n*   **Phone a Helpline:** If you feel overwhelmed by the loneliness, consider calling a helpline. They are there to listen.\n\n**4. Plan a Simple, Budget-Friendly \"Treat\":**\n\n*   **Make a Special Drink:** Use what you have to create a simple, festive drink.  Even adding a slice of lemon or orange to water can feel special.\n*   **Make popcorn:** A bag of popcorn is pretty cheap and it makes for a good pastime while watching a movie.\n*   **Cook Something Comforting:**  Raid your pantry and fridge and see what you can make.  Even a simple bowl of soup or toast with peanut butter can be comforting.\n\n**5. Limit Social Media:**\n\n*   **Comparison is the Thief of Joy:**  Seeing everyone else's \"perfect\" celebrations can amplify feelings of loneliness and inadequacy.  Minimize your time on social media.\n\n**6.  Reflect and Plan (Gently):**\n\n*   **Write Down a Few Goals (No Pressure):** Think about one or two small, achievable goals you'd like to work towards in the new year.  These don't have to be huge, life-changing goals \u2013 just something that will give you a sense of purpose. (e.g., \"Read one book a month,\" \"Go for a walk three times a week.\")\n*   **Journaling:** Write down your feelings. Sometimes, just putting them on paper can help you process them.\n\n**Important Reminders:**\n\n*   **This is Temporary:**  Remember that feelings of loneliness and financial hardship are often temporary.  Things can and will get better.\n*   **Be Kind to Yourself:**  Don't beat yourself up for feeling this way.  Acknowledge your feelings and treat yourself with compassion.\n*   **Seek Help if Needed:**  If you're struggling with depression or suicidal thoughts, please reach out for help.  Here are some resources:\n\n    *   **988 Suicide & Crisis Lifeline:** Call or text 988 in the US and Canada.  In the UK, dial 111.\n    *   **The Crisis Text Line:** Text HOME to 741741.\n    *   **The Trevor Project:** (For LGBTQ youth) 1-866-488-7386\n\n**Tomorrow, focus on getting through the day. Just one step at a time. Don't compare yourself to others.  Focus on what you *can* control \u2013 your actions, your thoughts, your self-care.  I'm sending you positive energy and hope that you find some moments of peace and comfort tomorrow.**\n",
